President Obama has issued a proclamation declaring April 28, 2015, as Workers Memorial Day. On this day, Americans are encouraged to honor and remember those who have lost their lives or been injured due to unsafe working conditions. The proclamation emphasizes the importance of improving workplace conditions and ensuring the safety and well-being of workers. The President highlights the progress made in reducing job-related deaths, injuries, and illnesses, but emphasizes the need for continued efforts in this area. The administration has taken steps to protect workers' rights and ensure workplace safety, including funding for inspections and compliance with safety regulations. The President also signed an Executive Order to hold federal contractors accountable for maintaining a safe workplace. The proclamation emphasizes the value of American workers and the need to prioritize their safety and well-being.